        "Feedback": "# Feedback\n\n### Correct Reasoning Steps\n\n1. **Understand Effective Duration**: Effective duration measures the sensitivity of a bond's price to a 100 bps parallel shift in the yield curve, assuming no change in the bond's credit spread.\n\n2. **Option-Free Bond (Bond #3)**: The effective duration of an option-free bond like Bond #3 changes very little in response to interest rate movements.\n\n3. **Callable Bond (Bond #4)**: When interest rates rise, a call option becomes less likely to be exercised (out of the money), which increases the bond's value and lengthens its effective duration.\n\n4. **Putable Bond (Bond #5)**: When interest rates rise, the put option becomes more likely to be exercised (in the money), which limits the bond's price depreciation and shortens its effective duration.\n\n5. **Conclusion**: Therefore, the bond whose effective duration will lengthen if interest rates rise is the callable bond, Bond #4.\n\n### Comparison with Wrong Reasoning\n\n- **Misinterpretation of Interest Rate Impact**: The wrong reasoning suggests that Bond #5 (putable) will have a lengthened effective duration when interest rates decrease. However, the correct reasoning is focused on how effective duration changes when interest rates rise. A callable bond (Bond #4) has its effective duration lengthen when interest rates rise, contrary to the wrong reasoning which misapplies the conditions.\n\n- **Focus on Callable vs. Putable**: The correct reasoning highlights the effect of interest rate changes on callable and putable bonds separately, emphasizing how a callable bond's duration behaves differently than a putable bond when rates rise.\n\n### Summary for Future Questions\n\n- **Understand the Bond Type**: Carefully consider the type of bond (callable, putable, option-free) and the effect of interest rate changes on each.\n\n- **Interest Rate Direction**: Pay close attention to whether the question asks about rising or falling interest rates and how each impacts the bond's options.\n\n- **Option Moneyness**: Recognize how the moneyness of options (in the money vs. out of the money) affects the bond's effective duration with interest rate movements.\n\nBy focusing on these aspects, you can accurately determine how a bond's effective duration is affected by changes in interest rates.",
