        "Feedback": "### Correct Reasoning Steps\n\nTo calculate Holt's Free Cash Flow to the Firm (FCFF) for 2020, follow these steps:\n\n1. **Net Income (NI):**\n   - Given as $485 million.\n\n2. **Add Back Non-Cash Charges (NCC - Depreciation):**\n   - Depreciation is $270 million.\n\n3. **Add Back Interest Expense (After-Tax):**\n   - Interest expense = $195 million.\n   - After-tax interest expense = $195 million x (1 - 0.32) = $132.6 million.\n\n4. **Calculate Capital Expenditures (FCInv):**\n   - Increase in gross fixed assets = $4,275 million - $3,752 million = $523 million.\n\n5. **Calculate Changes in Working Capital (WCInv):**\n   - Increase in Accounts Receivable = $770 million - $711 million = $59 million.\n   - Increase in Inventories = $846 million - $780 million = $66 million.\n   - Increase in Accounts Payable = $476 million - $443 million = $33 million.\n   - Increase in Accrued Liabilities = $149 million - $114 million = $35 million.\n   - Net increase in working capital = $59 + $66 - $33 - $35 = $57 million.\n\n6. **Calculate FCFF:**\n   $$\n   \\text{FCFF} = \\text{NI} + \\text{NCC} + \\text{Interest expense (1 - Tax rate)} - \\text{FCInv} - \\text{WCInv}\n   $$\n   $$\n   \\text{FCFF} = 485 + 270 + 132.6 - 523 - 57 = 307.6 \\text{ million (or } 308 \\text{ million)}\n   $$\n\n### Comparison with Wrong Reasoning\n\n- **Working Capital:** The wrong reasoning missed accounting for the increase in accrued liabilities.\n- **Calculation Errors:** The incorrect calculation led to a significant deviation in the FCFF value.\n  \n### Summary for Future Questions\n\n- **Always Consider All Components:** Ensure all changes in working capital, including liabilities, are considered.\n- **Double-Check Calculations:** Re-evaluate each step to ensure accuracy.\n- **Use Correct Formula:** FCFF = NI + NCC + Interest Expense (1 - Tax rate) - FCInv - WCInv.",
