        "Feedback": "### Feedback\n\n#### Correct Reasoning Steps\n\n1. **Understanding the Given Probabilities:**\n   - The probability that both Bond A and Bond B will default is given as 5% (0.05).\n   - If Bond A defaults, the probability that Bond B will also default is 50% (0.5).\n\n2. **Determine the Probability of Bond A Defaulting:**\n   - Denote the probability of Bond A defaulting as $ P(A) $.\n   - The probability that both Bond A and Bond B default $ P(A \\cap B) = 5\\% = 0.05 $.\n   - Using the rule of conditional probability:\n     $$\n     P(A \\cap B) = P(A) \\times P(B | A)\n     $$\n   - Substitute the known values:\n     $$\n     0.05 = P(A) \\times 0.5\n     $$\n   - Solve for $ P(A) $:\n     $$\n     P(A) = \\frac{0.05}{0.5} = 0.1\n     $$\n\n3. **Calculate the Probability of Bond B Defaulting:**\n   - Since both bonds have the same probability of default, $ P(B) = P(A) = 0.1 $.\n\n4. **Calculate the Probability that Neither Bond A nor Bond B Defaults:**\n   - Use the formula for the probability of the union of two events:\n     $$\n     P(A \\cup B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A \\cap B)\n     $$\n   - Calculate $ P(A \\cup B) $:\n     $$\n     P(A \\cup B) = 0.1 + 0.1 - 0.05 = 0.15\n     $$\n   - Therefore, the probability that neither bond defaults is:\n     $$\n     P(\\text{neither default}) = 1 - P(A \\cup B) = 1 - 0.15 = 0.85\n     $$\n\n5. **Conclusion:**\n   - The probability that neither Bond A nor Bond B will default over the next year is 85%, which corresponds to option C.\n\n#### Comparison with the Wrong Reasoning\n\n- The **wrong reasoning** incorrectly assumes independence in the calculation of the probability that neither bond defaults, using $ P(\\text{neither default}) = (1 - P(A)) \\times (1 - P(B)) = 0.9 \\times 0.9 = 0.81 $.\n- It **does not account** for the overlap in the probabilities where both bonds default simultaneously, which is an essential part of the question due to the conditional probability given.\n- The **correct reasoning** uses the addition rule for probabilities to account for the joint probability $ P(A \\cap B) $ and correctly calculates $ P(A \\cup B) $ to find the probability that neither bond defaults.\n\n#### Summary of the Hint for Similar Questions\n\n- When you have probabilities involving joint events and conditional probabilities, always use the rules of conditional probability and addition rule for probabilities.\n- Ensure to account for overlaps in events when calculating the probability of \"neither\" or \"none\" scenarios.\n- Avoid assuming independence unless explicitly stated; use given probabilities and relationships as outlined in the problem statement.",
